  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Bari who grew up in a small Italian town with a family that valued education but had different paths for men and women, I’ve seen how science has always been a field where men were encouraged more. My father had a vocational diploma and worked in construction, while my mother, who had a master’s degree, taught us about the natural world through gardening and cooking. When I was young, we didn’t have many role models in science—mostly men in labs and universities. The gender gap in science today is still very real, but it’s not just about numbers; it’s about the stories we tell ourselves. I’ve noticed that in my community, especially among older generations, there’s a belief that science is for the ‘strong’ and ‘logical’ minds, which often leans toward men. This is why fewer women pursue science careers. But addressing this gap isn’t about fixing something broken—it’s about changing the narrative. For example, in my neighborhood, when I volunteer at the local library, I often talk to young girls about how science can be creative, like cooking or painting. They’re not just interested in equations—they’re interested in how things work. So, the solution isn’t to push women into science but to show them that science is a part of life, not just a job. We need to make science accessible and relevant to everyone, especially girls who see themselves in the world beyond the lab. It’s about changing how we see ourselves and each other.",
